                <head>152. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On March 13, 1964, Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>,
                    accompanied by Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>,
                    testified on East-West trade before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. A
                    detailed draft outline of the Secretary’s testimony, prepared in <gloss
                        target="#t_SP1">S/P</gloss> on March 3, is attached to a March 3 memorandum
                    from <persName corresp="#p_FER1">Edward Fried</persName> to
                        <persName>Springsteen</persName>. (Department of State, <gloss
                        target="#t_SP1">S/P</gloss>C Files: Lot 70 <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss>
                    199, Economic Policy—1964) The transcript of his prepared statement (Department
                    of State Press Release No. 108, March 13) is ibid. <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>’s entire
                    testimony was subsequently published in <hi rend="italic">East-West Trade:
                        Hearings Before the Committee on Foreign Relations, United States Senate,
                        Eighty-eighth Congress, Second Session</hi> (Washington: Government Printing
                    Office, 1964), Part I, pp. 2–42. Part II of these hearings took place in
                    February 1965.</p>
            </div>
